        "bullets": [
            "A second commercial tanker has been abandoned by its crew within 24 hours after a projectile strike near the Strait of Hormuz, per gCaptain.",
            "Iranian state media claims the IRGC stopped a Kuwaiti tanker in the US-Omani corridor; the US reports vessels still transiting and has not confirmed a closure.",
            "Brent crude traded at $91.94 at 14:52 UTC, up +4.55% over 24 hours, as the Hormuz Index Crisis Pressure holds at extreme with Escalation Forecast at elevated."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-21",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-21T14:52:28.176Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "Operational conditions at the Strait of Hormuz have deteriorated sharply after a second commercial tanker was abandoned within 24 hours following a projectile strike, per gCaptain, bringing the total crew-abandonment count to two in a single day and signaling a new threshold in risk to mariners. The strait's status remains contested: Iranian state media and IRGC sources claim a closure and report the stopping of a Kuwaiti tanker transiting the US-Omani corridor, but these are unverified claims from flagged state media outlets with no independent confirmation. The US and CENTCOM report vessels still transiting and see no evidence of a physical closure. Port arrivals across Hormuz-area ports on both the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman sides reached 317 vessels in the most recent 24 hours, while PortWatch's most recent published day, 2026-07-19, recorded 15 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day. At 14:52 UTC, 459 vessels were anchored or stopped in the region. The Hormuz Index places Crisis Pressure in the extreme band, with physical transit deviation as the top contributor, while the Escalation Forecast sits in the elevated band driven by prediction-market signals; the two indices diverge, measuring current operational stress and forward risk respectively. Brent at $91.94 reflects a market that has priced significant but not total closure. Hull underwriters and P and I clubs should treat crew-abandonment events as a hard signal on war-risk pricing.",
